Every year, about 90 young, seemingly healthy athletes drop dead from sudden cardiac arrest. A screening test likely could prevent many of the deaths, but administering a screening electrocardiogram to all young athletes has been viewed as impractical and expensive.

Now an analysis published this week in The Annals of Internal Medicine suggests that a screening EKG for young athletes is more cost-effective than previously believed.

